Results

4.3.1 RQ1: Continuous Development Effectiveness. Table 1 summarizes the four long-running deployments. Across all projects,
TheBotCompany completed 164 milestones and 616 agent cycles
spanning 137 wall-clock hours, reaching the primary quality objective in every case without human intervention. No project exhibited
the degenerate behavior we guarded against. Cycle waste ratios
were low and only occurred in two projects: 5.3% in M2Sim, and
in RustLaTex, 27 fix-round milestones account for a 6.9% waste
ratio. Worker agents absorbed 70.6% of total token cost on average,
with Athena’s planning share remaining at 9.8%, confirming that
orchestration overhead does not crowd out implementation capacity as codebases grow. The projects also show that TheBotCompany adapts to widely varying task complexity without structural
change: GroundDB completed in 17 cycles with a tight correctness
oracle, while RustLaTex required 392 cycles as each layout change
interacted with competing rendering constraints—both trajectories
exhibit forward progress rather than oscillation.
Finding (RQ1): TheBotCompany sustained forward progress across
all four long-running projects, spanning four languages (Go, Python,
Rust, C++) and three architectural paradigms, completing 164 milestones, 616 cycles, and 137 wall-clock hours without human intervention beyond initial project configuration.
4.3.2 RQ2: Comparison with Single-Agent Baselines. Table 2 reports
scores on the five hard problems from ProjDevBench. TheBotCompany (sole Claude Sonnet 4.5) achieves a mean execution score of
53.2 and overall score of 70.0, leading all five single-agent baselines.

